{"timestamp": "2025-12-06 10:34:39.242040", "event": "llm_end", "text": "Troubleshooting Diagnosis Report\n\nExecutive summary\n- Layer-3 reachability across the enterprise network is healthy (no loss, low RTT). All key subnets and the server farm 10.200.0.0/24 are reachable from the user hosts.\n- The primary service-impacting anomaly is DNS: the DNS server at 10.200.0.2 (dns_server) is not answering queries, causing all hostname-based access (e.g., web99.local, web0.local) from hosts to fail. Access by IP works.\n- Additional inconsistencies: the “Apache” backend web servers have the apache2 service inactive while port 80 is still listening; and backend web servers are directly reachable from hosts, which contradicts the stated design intent.\n\nKey observations and evidence\n\n1) Reachability and routing\n- End-to-end ICMP reachability between hosts and server farm is good.\n  • host_1_1_1_1 → 10.200.0.7 (load_balancer): 0% loss, RTT avg ~3–6 ms\n  • host_2_1_1_1 → 10.200.0.4 (web_server_1): 0% loss, RTT avg ~3 ms\n  • Hosts successfully ping 10.200.0.2 (dns_server): 0% loss, RTT ~2–5 ms\n- This indicates OSPF distribution and basic IP forwarding are functioning as expected.\n\n2) HTTP application tests\n- By hostname from hosts:\n  • curl http://web99.local and http://web0.local from both hosts consistently show total ~5.0 s with namelookup 0.000 and no TTFB, consistent with DNS resolution failure followed by timeout.\n- By IP from hosts:\n  • curl http://10.200.0.7 (load_balancer VIP): succeeds with connect ~2–4 ms, TTFB ~200–700 ms, total ~1.0–1.5 s.\n  • curl http://10.200.0.3 (web_server_0): succeeds with similar timings.\n- Conclusion: HTTP services are reachable and respond over IP, but hostnames fail due to DNS resolution problems.\n\n3) DNS resolution behavior\n- Host DNS configuration:\n  • /etc/resolv.conf on both hosts: nameserver 10.200.0.2\n- Host-side DNS queries:\n  • From host_1_1_1_1: dig +time=2 +tries=1 @10.200.0.2 web99.local and web0.local → timed out (UDP). Same with +tcp → timed out.\n  • getent hosts web99.local / web0.local → command timed out.\n- On the DNS server itself (dns_server):\n  • named is running: rndc status shows BIND 9.18, active, up and running, listening threads present; “number of zones: 2” (likely only localhost/localnet defaults).\n  • netstat/ss show listeners on 10.200.0.2:53 and 127.0.0.1:53 for both TCP and UDP.\n  • However, dig @127.0.0.1 web99.local and @10.200.0.2 web99.local (UDP and TCP) both time out.\n  • iptables policies are ACCEPT; no obvious firewall drops on port 53.\n  • /etc/bind/named.conf.options is largely default; forwarders are commented out; no special ACLs configured; listen-on-v6 any; no explicit recursion disable.\n  • /etc/bind/named.conf.local is essentially empty; there is no local zone definition for the enterprise domain containing web*.local.\n- Interpretation:\n  • BIND is running and listening, but it is not answering queries. With no authoritative zones for the local names (web*.local) and no forwarders configured, named will attempt full recursion to public roots for any query outside its tiny default zones. In this lab environment without internet reachability, those outbound queries never complete, causing client queries to time out (observed both locally and from hosts).\n  • The presence of listeners and a healthy rndc status combined with timeouts to both 127.0.0.1 and 10.200.0.2 strongly indicate server-side resolver behavior is blocked waiting for upstream responses rather than a transport/ACL issue.\n\n4) Load balancer and backend servers\n- Load balancer:\n  • Nginx active (running); netstat shows :80 listening; reachable by IP and responds with normal timings.\n- Backend web servers:\n  • web_server_0..3 show 0.0.0.0:80 listening; however, apache2 service is inactive (dead) on all four. Despite apache2 being inactive, port 80 is open (another HTTP daemon could be listening) and responds to HTTP by IP (e.g., 10.200.0.3).\n- Policy observation:\n  • Hosts can ping and HTTP to backend servers directly by IP, which contradicts the design note that backend web servers should not be directly accessible from hosts. This suggests missing or ineffective segmentation/ACLs between access subnets and backend server subnets.\n\nFault localization\n- Primary fault localized to dns_server (10.200.0.2).\n  • Service-level: named process is up and listening but not providing responses to queries, even locally. Behavior consistent with a resolver stuck attempting recursion without available upstreams and lacking the authoritative local zone for web*.local.\n- Secondary issues:\n  • Web tier: apache2 services inactive across web_server_0..3 despite the design describing “Apache web servers.” Another service appears to be binding to port 80.\n  • Network policy: backend servers are directly reachable from user hosts, contrary to the stated design intent.\n\nRoot cause analysis\n- Root cause of application failure by hostname: DNS misconfiguration on dns_server.\n  • No authoritative zone data for the local domain hosting web0.local…web3.local and web99.local.\n  • Forwarders are not configured and the environment likely lacks internet egress for recursion to the public root. As a result, BIND attempts recursion and never receives upstream replies, leading to timeouts on all queries, including .local names.\n- Contributing/related findings:\n  • Backend servers’ Apache services are inactive, which is inconsistent with the stated server role, although HTTP still responds via some listener on port 80.\n  • Lack of traffic filtering permitting direct host-to-backend access.\n\nImpact assessment\n- All hostname-based service access from user hosts fails due to DNS timeouts (web99.local, web0.local, etc.). Clients can only access services by IP.\n- Load balancer functionality is intact via IP.\n- Routing and underlying L3 connectivity are normal; OSPF appears to be functioning.\n\nItems explicitly verified\n- ICMP reachability across hosts and servers: OK (0% loss).\n- DNS server process state: named active, listening on TCP/UDP 53.\n- DNS function: queries time out locally and from hosts (UDP and TCP).\n- HTTP services: reachable by IP (load balancer and backend servers).\n- Host resolver configuration: points to 10.200.0.2 as expected.\n\nNo remediation is proposed at this stage; this report focuses on detection, localization, and root cause identification.", "generation_info": {"finish_reason": "stop", "logprobs": null}, "invalid_tool_calls": [], "usage_metadata": {"input_tokens": 14534, "output_tokens": 5123, "total_tokens": 19657, "input_token_details": {"audio": 0, "cache_read": 13824}, "output_token_details": {"audio": 0, "reasoning": 3584}}}
